answer_text:
Regions in the ≥ 8 Mt class generate substantial surpluses after local use. Because they are geographically spread between western (France, Germany) and central Europe (Poland, Romania), they:

buffer shortfalls elsewhere in the EU;

underpin the bloc’s net-export position on wheat and barley;

reduce reliance on extra-EU imports in volatile years, thus strengthening European food security.
Concentration does, however, mean that weather or market shocks in a handful of regions can ripple through EU supply.

Explanation – A very high share of circulatory deaths reflects widespread cardiovascular risk factors (high smoking and alcohol prevalence, diets rich in salt and saturated fat, sub-optimal hypertension control) and limited access to rapid cardiac care. Cancer’s 20 % share is close to the EU average, while the high “other” share captures injury, liver disease and other alcohol-related conditions.
Implications for the state – Latvia faces:

Heavy demand on cardiology and emergency services;

Large productivity losses from early cardiovascular deaths;

The need for public-health action (tobacco, alcohol, salt reduction campaigns) and investment in primary prevention and treatment capacity.
